Let $\omega = e^{\frac{2\pi}{n}i} = \cos \frac{2\pi}{n} + i \sin \frac{2\pi}{n}$, a primitive $n$th root of unity. Then \begin{align*}
  \cos \frac{\pi}{n} \cos \frac{2\pi}{n} \cos \frac{4\pi}{n} \cos \frac{8\pi}{n}
     \cos \frac{16\pi}{n} &= \operatorname{Re} \omega \operatorname{Re} \omega^2 \operatorname{Re} \omega^4 \operatorname{Re} \omega^8 \operatorname{Re} \omega^{16} \\
             &= \frac{\operatorname{Re}(\omega^{31} - 1)}{15} \\
             &=-\frac{1}{15}.
\end{align*} because $\omega^{31} = \omega^{14 - 1} = \overline{\omega} = \omega^{-1}$ and $31 \equiv 15 \pmod{n}$. So we need to check the values of $n$ that make $\frac{1}{32}$ divisible by $-\frac{1}{15}$, i.e., $2^5$ divisible by $3^1 5^3$.</think> <answer>240,120,96,80,60,48,40,30. If the natural numbers $a,b,c$ satisfy $a \mid 48$, $b \mid 40$, and $c \mid 48$, then $abc = 4800$ has $10$ positive integer solutions, listed above.</answer>

